\end_inset

The Economics of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Tagging
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as Applied to the Optimal Income Tax, Welfare Programs, and Manpower Planning
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Akerlof (1978): Overview
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Why not use the tax system to target transfers to the poor?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Contrast two extreme cases:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Negative Income Tax: 
\begin_inset Formula $T=-\alpha\bar{Y}+tY$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{Y}$
\end_inset

 is per capita income, 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is marginal tax rate.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i}T=-\alpha n\bar{Y}+t\sum_{i}Y_{i}\Rightarrow t=\alpha+g\quad g\equiv\sum_{i}T_{i}/\sum_{i}Y_{i}
\]

\end_inset

Giving the poor a bigger transfer 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\alpha\right)$
\end_inset

 requires a one-for-one increase in 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Perfect tag: Imagine we can identify a group of size 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta n$
\end_inset

 that contains all the poor people and we give the amount 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 to everyone in this group.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t=\beta\alpha+g
\]

\end_inset

Giving more to the poor only costs 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta<1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Akerlof (1978): Simple Optimal Tax Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
2 types of workers, skilled & unskilled.
 Each 50% of the population
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
2 types of jobs.
 Easy and difficult.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Skilled worker's output in difficult job is 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{D}>q_{E}=$
\end_inset

 skilled worker's output in easy job
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Unskilled workers only work in the easy job.
 Produce output 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{E}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Workers in difficult job pay tax 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{D}$
\end_inset

.
 Utility of skilled workers in difficult job is 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(q_{D}-t_{D}\right)-\delta$
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Utility of both types in easy job is 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(q_{E}+t_{E}\right)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(q_{D}\right)-\delta>u\left(q_{E}\right)$
\end_inset

 (otherwise everyone always takes easy job).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Akerlof (1978): Simple Optimal Tax Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Government chooses 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{D},t_{E}$
\end_inset

 to maximize expected utility
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=\tfrac{1}{2}\max\left\{ u\left(q_{D}-t_{D}\right)-\delta,u\left(q_{E}+t_{E}\right)\right\} +\tfrac{1}{2}u\left(q_{E}+t_{E}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Budget balance requires
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
t_{D} & =t_{E}\quad\text{if}\quad u\left(q_{D}-t_{D}\right)-\delta\geq u\left(q_{E}+t_{E}\right)\\
t_{E} & =0\quad\text{if}\quad u\left(q_{D}-t_{D}\right)-\delta<u\left(q_{E}+t_{E}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Optimum:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
t_{D}^{*}=t_{E}^{*} & \quad\text{(budget balance)}\\
u\left(q_{D}-t_{D}^{*}\right)-\delta=u\left(q_{E}+t_{E}^{*}\right) & \quad\text{(binding IC)}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Akerlof (1978): Tagging in Simple Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Introduce tagging: A proportion 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 of the poor have an observable tag.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Difficult job taxed 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{D}$
\end_inset

.
 Untagged in easy job get 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{E}$
\end_inset

.
 Tagged get 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Government problem is now
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\max_{T_{D},T_{E},\tau}U^{Tag} & =\tfrac{1}{2}\max\left\{ u\left(q_{D}-T_{D}\right)-\delta,u\left(q_{E}+T_{E}\right)\right\} \\
 & \quad+\tfrac{1}{2}\left(1-\beta\right)u\left(q_{E}+T_{E}\right)+\tfrac{1}{2}\beta u\left(q_{E}+\tau\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Subject to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
T_{D}=\left(1-\beta\right)T_{E}+\beta\tau & \text{ if }u\left(q_{D}-T_{D}\right)-\delta\geq u\left(q_{E}+T_{E}\right)\\
\left(2-\beta\right)T_{E}+\beta\tau=0 & \text{ if }u\left(q_{D}-T_{D}\right)-\delta<u\left(q_{E}+T_{E}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Akerlof (1978): Tagging Optimum
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Optimum features binding IC constraint
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u\left(q_{D}-T_{D}^{*}\right)-\delta=u\left(q_{E}+T_{E}^{*}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
More importantly, tagging allows more redistribution: 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{*}>t_{E}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Rough proof by contradiction: Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{*}\leq T_{E}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Consider reducing 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{E}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 and increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Nobody is worse off (envelope theorem)
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
This perturbation raises revenue
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
This revenue can be used to redistribute
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Argument item:1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{*}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{E}^{*}$
\end_inset

 is not optimally set
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Akerlof (1978): Tags
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
What makes a good tag?
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Easily Observable.
 Low admin costs of using the tag
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Correlated with need.
 Good at discriminating between needy and not (high 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Immutable.
 People can't endogenously acquire the tag
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

