\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Can it be optimal to give some of the transfer through an in-kind transfer
 instead of its cash equivalent?
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Usually, we think people must be at least as well off with the cash, so
 no.
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This is the case when demand depends only on its price and income (i.e.
 it's independent of leisure, ability, other observables).
 When it doesn't, it might act as a tag.
 N&Z call these 
\emph on
Indicator goods
\emph default

\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Return to the simple income tax model.
 Out of total income 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{Y}+T$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 buys 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}^{*}$
\end_inset

 of good 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 (at price 1).
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 masquerades, she would only buy 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}_{A}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is an indicator good.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

