Workfare versus Welfare: Incentive Arguments for Work Requirements in Poverty-Al
leviation Programs
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Besley & Coate (1992): Overview
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Should people who receive transfers be required to work in exchange?
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Common policy, but is it efficient? 2 possible reasons
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Screening
\emph default
.
 When we can't (easily) observe earnings (ability), work requirement 
\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow$
\end_inset

 self-targeting
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Deterrence.

\emph default
 Encourage poverty-reducing investments
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
B&C formalize this, provide sufficient conditions for workfare to dominate
 cash transfers.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Besley & Coate (1992): Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 individuals.
 Fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 of low types have ability 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{L}<a_{H}=$
\end_inset

 ability of high types
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(y,l\right)=y-h\left(l\right)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Poverty-alleviation program: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b_{i},c_{i}\right\} _{i=L,H}$
\end_inset

.
 Transfer 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}$
\end_inset

 and requirement of 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}$
\end_inset

 hours of work.
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
PAP costs 
\begin_inset Formula $n\left[\gamma b_{L}+\left(1-\gamma\right)b_{H}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Government objective is to minimize cost of guaranteeing everyone income
 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Besley & Coate (1992): Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Individuals who accept 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b_{i},c_{i}\right\} $
\end_inset

 can also provide private-sector labor:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
l\left(b,c,a_{i}\right)=\begin{cases}
\hat{l}\left(a_{i}\right)-c & \text{if }c\leq\hat{l}\left(a_{i}\right)\\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{l}$
\end_inset

 is optimal labor supply without PAP 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(h^{\prime}\left(\hat{l}\right)=a_{i}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Yields private-sector earnings
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y\left(c,a_{i}\right)=\begin{cases}
a_{i}\left[\hat{l}\left(a_{i}\right)-c\right] & \text{if }c\leq\hat{l}\left(a_{i}\right)\\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
and indirect utility
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v\left(b,c,a_{i}\right)=b+y\left(c,a_{i}\right)-h\left(l\left(c,a_{i}\right)+c\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Besley & Coate (1992): Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Individuals will take the package intended for them iff
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v\left(b_{i},c_{i},a_{i}\right)\geq v\left(0,0,a_{i}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Assume that only the 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 types are poor without government intervention
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y\left(0,a_{H}\right)>z>y\left(0,a_{L}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Besley & Coate (1992): First-best benchmark
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Suppose policymakers observe abilities 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{L},a_{H}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Now the government has to satisfy two constraints:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Participation constraints: 
\begin_inset Formula $v\left(b_{i},c_{i},a_{i}\right)\geq v\left(0,0,a_{i}\right),\;i=L,H$
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 types must escape poverty: 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{L}+y\left(c_{L},a_{L}\right)\geq z$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\shape smallcaps
proposition 1
\shape default
: 
\emph on
Cost-minimizing PSP is a welfare program.
 Low-ability individuals are offered a cash transfer that is just high enough
 to get them out of poverty, 
\begin_inset Formula $z-y\left(0,a_{L}\right)$
\end_inset

, and high-ability individuals are offered no benefits.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Besley & Coate (1992): Screening
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Now suppose, govt only knows 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, the proportion of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 types.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Now the government also needs to respect incentive compatibility constraints:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v\left(b_{L},c_{L},a_{L}\right)\geq v\left(b_{H},c_{H},a_{L}\right)\quad v\left(b_{H},c_{H},a_{H}\right)\geq v\left(b_{L},c_{L},a_{H}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Note, without work requirements, these imply 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{L}=b_{H}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The work requirement will allow the government to screen because 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 types have a higher opportunity cost of government work.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
But, the work requirement reduces the 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 types' income, so requires a bigger transfer to get them back to 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{L}=z$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Tradeoff of increasing work requirement: lower transfers to 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 to respect IC, and higher transfers to 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 to achieve 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{L}=z$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Besley & Coate (1992): Screening
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Define the 
\emph on
separating work requirement
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{L}^{s}$
\end_inset

 that gets the poor out of poverty and prevents masquerading
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v\left(0,0,a_{H}\right)=v\left(z-y\left(c_{L}^{s},a_{L}\right),c_{L}^{s},a_{H}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\shape smallcaps
proposition 2
\shape default
: 
\emph on
If both income-generating abilities and incomes are unobservable, one of
 the following two PAPs is cost-minimizing: (i) (welfare) impose no work
 requirements and offer both ability groups a transfer of 
\begin_inset Formula $z=y\left(0,a_{L}\right)$
\end_inset

; (ii) (workfare) offer self-categorized high-ability individuals no benefits
 and offer self-categorized low-ability individuals a transfer of 
\begin_inset Formula $z-y\left(c_{L}^{s},a\right)$
\end_inset

 in exchange for a work requirement of 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{L}^{s}$
\end_inset

.
 A sufficient condition for the workfare solution to be cost-minimizing
 is that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{L}<\left(1-\gamma\right)a_{H}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Besley & Coate (1992): Screening
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
In the previous case we assumed the government can't observe earnings (so
 transfers can't depend on earnings).
 
\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When the government 
\emph on
can
\emph default
 observe earnings, to mimic the low type, the high type must reduce her
 earnings to 
\begin_inset Formula $y\left(c_{L},a_{L}\right)$
\end_inset

, requiring labor supply 
\begin_inset Formula $y\left(c_{L},a_{L}\right)/a_{H}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We might even be able to implement the first-best benchmark if
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v\left(0,0,a_{H}\right)\geq z-h\left(\frac{y\left(0,a_{L}\right)}{a_{H}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

(
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 prefers no benefit to earning 
\begin_inset Formula $y\left(0,a_{L}\right)$
\end_inset

 and consuming 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If this condition isn't met, we have to satisfy the IC constraint
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v\left(b_{H},c_{H},a_{H}\right)\geq b_{L}+y\left(c_{L},a_{L}\right)-h\left(\frac{y\left(c_{L},a_{L}\right)}{a_{H}}+c_{L}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Besley & Coate (1992): Screening
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Again, define the separating work requirement that satisfies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v\left(0,0,a_{H}\right)=z-h\left(\frac{y\left(\hat{c}_{L}^{s},a_{L}\right)}{a_{H}}+\hat{c}_{L}^{s}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\shape smallcaps
proposition 3:
\shape default
 
\emph on
If income-generating abilities are unobservable, individuals' incomes are
 observable and the benchmark PAP is not implementable, one of the following
 two programs is cost-minimizing: (i) (welfare) impose no work requirements
 and offer self-categorized high-ability individuals a transfer of 
\begin_inset Formula $z-h\left(y\left(0,a_{L}\right)/a_{H}\right)-v\left(0,0,a_{H}\right)$
\end_inset

 and offer self-categorized low-ability individuals a transfer of 
\begin_inset Formula $z-y\left(0,a_{L}\right)$
\end_inset

; (ii) (workfare) offer self-categorized high-ability individuals no benefits
 and offer self-categorized low-ability individuals a transfer of 
\begin_inset Formula $z-y\left(\hat{c}_{L}^{s},a_{L}\right)$
\end_inset

 in exchange for a work requirement of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c}_{L}^{s}$
\end_inset

.
 A sufficient condition for the workfare solution to be cost-minimizing
 is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma a_{L}<\left(1-\gamma\right)h^{\prime}\left(\frac{y\left(0,a_{L}\right)}{a_{H}}\right)\left(1-\frac{a_{L}}{a_{H}}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Besley & Coate (1992): Deterrence
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Assume again that the government observes ability.
 However ability depends on effort earlier in life.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Probability of being high ability is 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\left(e\right)$
\end_inset

 (strictly concave), costs 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Individuals will choose 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 to maximize
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi\left(e\right)v\left(b_{H},c_{H},a_{H}\right)+\left[1-\pi\left(e\right)\right]v\left(b_{L},c_{L},a_{L}\right)-e
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $e^{*}$
\end_inset

 increasing in ex-post difference between high- and low-ability
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e^{*}\left(\chi\left(\cdot\right)\right)\quad\chi\left(b_{L},c_{L},b_{H},c_{H}\right)\equiv v\left(b_{H},c_{H},a_{H}\right)-v\left(b_{L},c_{L},a_{L}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Besley & Coate (1992): Deterrence
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Define the 
\emph on
maximal work requirement
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{L}^{m}$
\end_inset

 that satisfies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v\left(z-y\left(c_{L}^{m},a_{L}\right),c_{L}^{m},a_{L}\right)=v\left(0,0,a_{L}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{L}^{m}>\hat{l}\left(a_{L}\right)$
\end_inset

 and so the low-ability individuals do not work.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\shape smallcaps
proposition 4: 
\shape default
\emph on
If income-generating abilities are observable but depend partly on choices
 made earlier in life, the cost-minimizing PAP either imposes no work requiremen
ts and offers low-ability individuals a transfer of 
\begin_inset Formula $z-y\left(0,a_{L}\right)$
\end_inset

, or imposes the maximal work requirement 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{L}^{m}$
\end_inset

 on low-ability individuals and offers them a transfer of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection
Niehaus, Atanassova, Bertrand & Mullainathan (AEJ:Pol 2013) 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


