\end_layout

\end_inset

Targeting with Agents
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Niehaus et al (2013): Overview
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
How should targeting rules be designed when they must be implemented by
 corruptible agents?
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Consider a proxy means test (PMT) that must be implemented by an official
 who may be corrupt.
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Show that having more indicators (which makes identifying the poor easier
 statistically) can backfire if enforcement is weak, by making it easier
 to pretend that ineligible households are eligible and hence easier to
 receive bribes.
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Test the theory with data on Below Poverty Line (BPL) cards in Karnataka,
 India.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Niehaus et al (2013): Households
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The principal wants to allocate slots among a set of households.
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Household 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 has 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Income 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}\in\left\{ \underline{y},\overline{y}\right\} $
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
other characteristics 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{i}\in\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Values the slot at 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}\sim G\left(v_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

, exponential with rate 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\eta$
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Joint distribution of attributes is 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(y_{i},\mathbf{x}_{i}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Niehaus et al (2013): Official
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Principal would like to use 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 for targeting, but it's unobserved.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Instead, use easier to observe characteristics 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A targeting rule is a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $R\subseteq\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

: A household is eligible iff 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{i}\in R$
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The official (agent) 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Implements 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Observes 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i},\mathbf{x}_{i}$
\end_inset

, but not 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Cares about his income 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and the allocation.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U\left(Y,\left\{ a_{i}\right\} \right)=Y+\underline{\alpha}\int_{y_{i}=\underline{y}}a_{i}di+\overline{\alpha}\int_{y_{i}=\overline{y}}a_{i}di
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

 indicates whether household 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 gets a slot; 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\underline{\alpha},\overline{\alpha}\right)$
\end_inset

 summarize the official's distributive preferences
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Niehaus et al (2013): Official
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
If official violates 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, he is caught with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\left(a_{i},\mathbf{x}_{i},R\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\left(a,\mathbf{x},R\right)=0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\mathbf{1}\left\{ \mathbf{x}\in R\right\} $
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\left(a,\mathbf{x},R\right)>0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq\mathbf{1}\left\{ \mathbf{x}\in R\right\} $
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Punishment is a fine 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Official allocates slots by establishing a menu of prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(y_{i},\mathbf{x}_{i}\right)\geq0$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\max_{\left\{ p_{i}\right\} }\int\left[1-G\left(p_{i}\right)\right]\left[p_{i}-c\left(y_{i},\mathbf{x}_{i}\right)\right]dF\left(y_{i},\mathbf{x}_{i}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where the implicit marginal cost 
\begin_inset Formula $c\left(y_{i},\mathbf{x}_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c\left(y_{i},\mathbf{x}_{i}\right)=f\left[\pi\left(1,\mathbf{x}_{i},R\right)-\pi\left(0,\mathbf{x}_{i},R\right)\right]-\underline{\alpha}\mathbf{1}\left\{ y_{i}=\underline{y}\right\} -\overline{\alpha}\mathbf{1}\left\{ y_{i}=\overline{y}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Niehaus et al (2013): Official
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The official's problem looks just like a monopolist's problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The solution will satisfy MR = MC, markups follow the rule 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(p-c\right)/p=-1/\epsilon$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p^{*}\left(y_{i},\mathbf{x}_{i}\right)=\max\left\{ 0,c\left(y_{i},\mathbf{x}_{i}\right)+\eta\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The probability that household 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 gets a slot is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\textsf{Pr}\left(a_{i}=1\vert\mathbf{x}_{i},y_{i}\right)=1-G\left(\max\left\{ 0,c\left(y_{i},\mathbf{x}_{i}\right)+\eta\right\} \right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Comparative statics:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
prices increase in income iff 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{\alpha}>\overline{\alpha}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
prices decrease in eligibility (strictly if 
\begin_inset Formula $f>0$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is sufficiently large, all eligible households get a slot at price 0.
 But might require arbitrarily harsh penalties, which seems unlikely.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Niehaus et al (2013): Principal
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Principal values the poor's surplus at 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{\omega}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly for the rich at 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\omega}<1/\eta<\underline{\omega}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Normalize cost of slots to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
V\left(\left\{ p_{i}\right\} \right) & =\int_{y_{i}=\underline{y}}\mathbf{1}\left\{ v_{i}>p_{i}\right\} \left[\underline{\omega}\left(v_{i}-p_{i}\right)-1\right]dG\left(v_{i}\right)dF\left(y_{i},\mathbf{x}_{i}\right)\\
 & \quad+\int_{y_{i}=\overline{y}}\mathbf{1}\left\{ v_{i}>p_{i}\right\} \left[\overline{\omega}\left(v_{i}-p_{i}\right)-1\right]dG\left(v_{i}\right)dF\left(y_{i},\mathbf{x}_{i}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Using the exponential distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(v_{i}\right)=e^{-v_{i}/\eta}/\eta$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
V\left(\left\{ p_{i}\right\} \right) & =\left(\underline{\omega}\eta-1\right)\int_{y_{i}=\underline{y}}e^{-p_{i}/\eta}dF\left(y_{i},\mathbf{x}_{i}\right)\\
 & \quad+\left(\overline{\omega}\eta-1\right)\int_{y_{i}=\overline{y}}e^{-p_{i}/\eta}dF\left(y_{i},\mathbf{x}_{i}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Niehaus et al (2013): When agency doesn't matter
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Contrast with the case where the agent is completely honest, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{i}\in R$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}=\infty$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{i}\notin R$
\end_inset

.
 Now, principal solves
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\max_{R\subseteq\mathbf{X}} & \left(\underline{\omega}\eta-1\right)\int_{y_{i}=\underline{y}}\mathbf{1}\left\{ \mathbf{x}_{i}\in R\right\} dF\left(y_{i},\mathbf{x}_{i}\right)\\
 & +\left(\overline{\omega}\eta-1\right)\int_{y_{i}=\overline{y}}\mathbf{1}\left\{ \mathbf{x}_{i}\in R\right\} dF\left(y_{i},\mathbf{x}_{i}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\shape smallcaps
proposition 1:
\shape default
 
\emph on
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{*}$
\end_inset

 be statistically optimal (solves above equation).
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
As 
\begin_inset Formula $f\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 the payoff from 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{*}$
\end_inset

 approaches the constrained optimal payoff.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
As 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{\alpha}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\alpha}\rightarrow-\infty$
\end_inset

 the payoff from 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{*}$
\end_inset

 approaches the constrained optimal payoff.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{\alpha}=\overline{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\pi}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\left(a_{i},\mathbf{x}_{i},R\right)=\tilde{\pi}\cdot\mathbf{1}\left\{ a_{i}\neq\mathbf{1}\left\{ \mathbf{x}_{i}\in R\right\} \right\} $
\end_inset

 then rule 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{*}$
\end_inset

 yields at least as high a payoff as any other nontrivial rule.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Niehaus et al (2013): When agency doesn't matter
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
In any of these cases agency issues are unimportant: Principal wants to
 use the statistically optimal rule.
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Third case is the interesting one: What does 
\emph on

\begin_inset Formula $\pi\left(a_{i},\mathbf{x}_{i},R\right)=\tilde{\pi}\cdot\mathbf{1}\left\{ a_{i}\neq\mathbf{1}\left\{ \mathbf{x}_{i}\in R\right\} \right\} $
\end_inset

 
\emph default
mean?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Principal detects deviations from 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 with pr 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\pi}$
\end_inset

, 
\emph on
regardless of what 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is.
 
\emph default
(e.g.
 random audits which fully verify 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{i}\in/\notin R$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
That means the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 doesn't affect how likely it is that the principal can detect deviations.
\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
That means the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 doesn't affect the official's incentives to deviate from 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Every household is equally risky.
\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Then changing 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 to make one household eligible won't affect the probability that any other
 households get a slot.
\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Now question of what 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 should be is only question of whether 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 includes eligible households, the statistical question.
