\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Basic strategy is to use cities where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{c}=0$
\end_inset

 to estimate the counterfactual:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{c}\left(z\vert\boldsymbol{\tau}\neq\mathbf{0},\lambda_{c}=0\right)=F_{c}\left(z\vert\boldsymbol{\tau}=\mathbf{0},\lambda_{c}=0\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
How to measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{c}$
\end_inset

? Use the degree of sharp bunching at 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Denote the fraction of individuals reporting 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}_{i}=K$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{c}=\theta_{c}\lambda_{c}$
\end_inset

 and so
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\shape smallcaps
assumption 1
\shape default
 (Tax Knowledge): 
\emph on
Individuals in neighborhoods with no sharp bunching at the kink have no
 knowledge of the policy’s marginal incentives and perceive 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\tau}=0$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{c}=0\Rightarrow\lambda_{c}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Under assumption 1 cities with no bunching reveal the distribution when
 there are no taxes:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{c}\left(z\vert\boldsymbol{\tau}\neq\mathbf{0},\phi_{c}=0\right)=F_{c}\left(z\vert\boldsymbol{\tau}=\mathbf{0},\phi_{c}=0\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

