\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Individuals have common utility 
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(x_{j}\right)-v\left(h_{j}\right)$
\end_inset

 if they do not apply
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(x_{j}\right)-v\left(h_{j}\right)-\left(\bar{\Lambda}\kappa_{j}+c\right)$
\end_inset

 if they apply
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Disutility from applying:
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

: individual-specific utility cost of applying.
 has distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{j}\left(c\right)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\Lambda}$
\end_inset

: parameter affecting utility cost
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{j}$
\end_inset

: how this utility cost varies across types.
 e.g.
 ordeals can impose greater utility cost on 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 types 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\kappa_{H}>\kappa_{L}\right)$
\end_inset

 or low types 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\kappa_{H}<\kappa_{L}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Finkelstein & Notowidigdo (2019): Framework
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Individuals make application and labor supply choices.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Type 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

s work 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{j}^{A}$
\end_inset

 hours if they apply, 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{j}^{-A}$
\end_inset

 if they don't.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Low types: assume 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}^{A},y_{j}^{-A}<r^{*}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
High types: assume 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}^{-A}>r^{*}$
\end_inset

 and to get the benefit, if apply 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{H}^{A}=r^{*}/\theta_{H}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
NB 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{j}^{A}\leq h_{j}^{-A}$
\end_inset

 for both types
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Individuals with 
\begin_inset Formula $c<c_{j}^{*}$
\end_inset

 will apply.
 Private welfare is therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
V_{j} & =\mathbb{P}\left(\text{apply}\right)\mathbb{E}\left[U\left(\right)\vert\text{apply}\right]+\mathbb{P}\left(\not\text{apply}\right)\mathbb{E}\left[U\left(\right)\vert\not\text{apply}\right]\\
 & =\int_{0}^{c_{j}^{*}}\left(u\left(y_{j}^{A}+B\right)-v\left(h_{j}^{A}\right)-\bar{\Lambda}\kappa_{j}-c\right)dF_{j}\text{\left(c\right)}\\
 & \quad+\int_{c_{j}^{*}}^{\infty}\left(u\left(y_{j}^{-A}\right)-v\left(h_{j}^{-A}\right)\right)dF_{j}\left(c\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Finkelstein & Notowidigdo (2019): Framework
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Individuals' decisions create a fiscal externality: Their hours decisions
 change tax revenue and this has a social cost that they don't internalize.
 For people who apply, the fiscal externality is 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{j}^{A}=\tau\left(h_{j}^{A}\theta_{j}\right)$
\end_inset

 while for those who don't it's 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{j}^{-A}=\tau\left(h_{j}^{-A}\theta_{j}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We can write total social welfare as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
W & =\underbrace{V_{L}+V_{H}}_{\text{Private Welfare}}-\underbrace{B\text{\left(A_{L}+A_{H}\right)}}_{\text{Program Cost}}\\
 & \quad+\underbrace{A_{L}G_{L}^{A}+\left(1-A_{L}\right)G_{L}^{-A}+A_{H}G_{H}^{A}+\left(1-A_{H}\right)G_{H}^{-A}}_{\text{Fiscal Externality}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{j}=F_{j}\left(c^{*}\right)$
\end_inset

, the expected number of applicants of type 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Planner chooses tax system 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\left(\right)$
\end_inset

 and transfer program (including ordeal 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\Lambda}$
\end_inset

) to maximize 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Finkelstein & Notowidigdo (2019): Framework
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Characterize the marginal effects on welfare of the two treatments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Information treatment: Increase perceived benefits by 
\begin_inset Formula $d\epsilon$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Information plus assistance: increase benefits 
\begin_inset Formula $d\epsilon$
\end_inset

 and reduce cost of applying, 
\begin_inset Formula $-d\bar{\Lambda}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Define:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{j}\equiv u\left(y_{j}^{A}+B\right)-u\left(y_{j}^{A}+\left(1+\epsilon_{j}\right)B\right)\quad\text{and }\quad\xi_{j}\equiv u^{\prime}\left(y_{j}^{A}+B\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Finkelstein & Notowidigdo (2019): Framework
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
We can write the effect of the information treatment on welfare as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{dW}{dT}^{\text{Information only}} & =\underbrace{\mu_{L}\frac{dA_{L}}{dT}+\mu_{H}\frac{dA_{H}}{dT}}_{\text{Change in Private Welfare}}\\
 & \quad-\underbrace{B\left(\frac{dA_{L}}{dT}+\frac{dA_{H}}{dT}\right)}_{\text{Change in Mechanical Program Costs}}\\
 & \quad+\underbrace{\left(G_{L}^{A}-G_{L}^{-A}\right)\frac{dA_{L}}{dT}+\left(G_{H}^{A}-G_{H}^{-A}\right)\frac{dA_{H}}{dT}}_{\text{Fiscal Externality}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Finkelstein & Notowidigdo (2019): Framework
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
We can write the effect of the information plus assistance treatment as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{dW}{dT}^{\text{Information + Assistance}} & =\underbrace{\mu_{L}\frac{dA_{L}}{dT}+\mu_{H}\frac{dA_{H}}{dT}+\kappa_{L}A_{L}+\kappa_{H}A_{H}}_{\text{Change in Private Welfare}}\\
 & \quad-\underbrace{B\left(\frac{dA_{L}}{dT}+\frac{dA_{H}}{dT}\right)}_{\text{Change in Mechanical Program Costs}}\\
 & \quad+\underbrace{\left(G_{L}^{A}-G_{L}^{-A}\right)\frac{dA_{L}}{dT}+\left(G_{H}^{A}-G_{H}^{-A}\right)\frac{dA_{H}}{dT}}_{\text{Fiscal Externality}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Finkelstein & Notowidigdo (2019): Framework
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Define targeting as 
\begin_inset Formula $e=E_{L}/\left(E_{L}+E_{H}\right)$
\end_inset

, the share of enrollees who are 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 types.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Then a treatment 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 increases targeting if 
\begin_inset Formula $de/dT>0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Holding constant the change in applications due to an intervention, the
 change in social welfare in response to an improvement in targeting 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(de/dT>0\right)$
\end_inset

 from an Information Only (or Information Plus Assistance) treatment is
 given by the following expression:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial\left(de/dT\right)}\left(\frac{dW}{dT}\right)\right|_{\frac{dA}{dT}} & =\left[\left(\mu_{L}-\mu_{H}\right)+\left(G_{L}^{A}-G_{L}^{-A}\right)-\left(G_{H}^{A}-G_{H}^{-A}\right)\right]\\
 & \quad\times\left(E_{H}+E_{L}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Note this is increasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{L}-\mu_{H}$
\end_inset

.
 Sufficient condition for better targeting to increase private welfare is
 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{L}\leq\epsilon_{H}\leq0$
\end_inset

 with at least 1 strict inequality, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{H}=\epsilon_{L}<0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Finkelstein & Notowidigdo (2019): Empirical Setting
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Work with households aged 60 or over in Pennsylvania in 2016
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To enroll in SNAP, individuals must complete an application, provide documents
 verifying circumstances, and do an interview (in person or by phone).
 Provide info on income, various household expenses (medical expenses, rent,
 utilities etc).
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Once enrolled, eligible for 36 months of benefits.
 Benefits are a decreasing function of net income.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
SNAP benefits average 15% of annual income for eligible households.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Finkelstein & Notowidigdo (2019): Interventions
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Partnered with Benefits Data Trust (BDT), a national non-profit working
 to help people access benefits.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
State of Pennsylvania provided BDT admin data on individuals aged >60 and
 on Medicaid but not SNAP.
 Likely to be eligible for SNAP.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Randomized the 30K individuals into equally-sized groups.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Information Treatment got outreach materials informing them of likely SNAP
 eligibility and benefits they might receive, and info on how to call DHS
 to apply.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Assistance component: Info Treatment contained BDT number.
 If individuals call BDT, they help with the application.
 Advise on documents, can populate and submit application on their behalf
 etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
BDT submitted 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim70\%$
\end_inset

 of applications in this treatment arm, spent on average 47 mins on phone
 with applicants, 30 with those who don't end up applying.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

