\end_inset

Targeting Impact versus Deprivation
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Haushofer Et Al (2022): Motivation
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Targeting is important in anti-poverty programs.
 Big literature now on how to identify 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

deprived
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (low wealth/consumption/living standards etc) households (Alatas et al
 2012; Blumenstock et al 2015; Brown et al 2018; hanna & Olken 2018,...)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
But there's more to it than just looking for currently deprived households.
 In general we also want to consider how much each household would benefit
 from assistance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Accumulating evidence of heterogeneous treatment effects, even of cash assistanc
e (de Mel et al 2008; Hussam et al 2022; Haushofer & Shapiro 2016)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This paper combines these insights.
 Build on ML methods to identify heterogeneity of treatment effects (Wager
 & Athey 2018; Chernozukhov et al 2018; Athey et al 2019) and conceptual
 framework to think about targeting on deprivation or on impact.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Haushofer Et Al (2022): Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Need to allocate a treatment to a subset of households 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 to maximize social welfare:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{h}\sum_{t=0}^{\bar{t}}W\left(Y_{h,t}\left(T_{h}\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{h,t}$
\end_inset

 is outcome (consumption, wealth etc) in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{h}\in\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

 is treatment assignment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Welfare function 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{\prime}>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{\prime\prime}\leq0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Using potential outcomes notation 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{h,t}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{h,t}^{0}$
\end_inset

 rewrite as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{h}\sum_{t=0}^{\bar{t}}W\left(Y_{h,t}^{0}+T_{h}\Delta_{h,t}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{h,t}^{0}$
\end_inset

 is the untreated PO and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{h,t}\equiv Y_{h,t}^{1}-Y_{h,t}^{0}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Haushofer Et Al (2022): Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Government can't observe each household's 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{h,t}^{0}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{h,t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Instead, observe 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
baseline covariates 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{h}\in\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Realized outcomes from an experimental sub-sample: 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{h,t}^{T_{h}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Select a rule 
\begin_inset Formula $r:\mathbf{X}\rightarrow\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

 to assign treatment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
With the experimental data, the planner can form predictions
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\hat{Y}_{t}^{0}\left(X_{h}\right) & \text{ of }\mathbb{E}\left[Y_{h,t}^{0}\vert X_{h},t\right]\\
\hat{\Delta}_{t}\left(X_{h}\right) & \text{ of }\mathbb{E}\left[Y_{h,t}^{1}-Y_{h,t}^{0}\vert X_{h},t\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Haushofer Et Al (2022): Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
With the predictions, the planner can target.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
e.g.
 target deprivation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r^{D}\left(X_{h}\right)=\mathbf{1}\left(\hat{Y}_{0}^{0}\left(X_{h}\right)\leq q_{\phi}^{\hat{Y}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
or; e.g.
 target impact:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r^{I}\left(X_{h}\right)=\mathbf{1}\left(\hat{\Delta}\left(X_{h}\right)\geq q_{1-\phi}^{\hat{\Delta}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
or target (social) welfare gain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
d\hat{W}\left(X_{h}\right) & \equiv\sum_{t=0}^{\bar{t}}\left[W\left(\hat{Y}_{t}^{0}\left(X_{h}\right)+\hat{\Delta}_{t}\left(X_{h}\right)\right)-W\left(\hat{Y}_{t}^{0}\left(X_{h}\right)\right)\right]\\
r^{*}\left(X_{h}\right) & =\mathbf{1}\left(d\hat{W}_{h}\geq q_{1-\phi}^{d\hat{W}}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Haushofer Et Al (2022): Intervention
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Use the intervention studied in Egger et al.
 (2022).
 Give Directly (GD) cash transfers in western Kenya.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
653 villages in 84 sublocations.
 Transfers between 2014 and 2017.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
GD defines households with thatched roofs as eligible 
\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow$
\end_inset

 35-40% of hhs eligible.
 Eligible hhs receive $1,000: 75% of mean annual expenditures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
2-level randomization:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
randomly assign 33 sub-locations to high saturation, 35 to low-saturation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
in High saturation sub-locations, 2/3 villages treated.
 In low, 1/3.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Baseline and endline surveys 
\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow$
\end_inset

 4,749 eligible households with both baseline & endline data on PMT inputs
 (hh size, children's ages, asset ownership, employment status etc)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
