Transfer Design: What is the Benefit?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Bryan, Chowdhury, Mobarak, Morten & Smits (2021) 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
protect
\backslash
textit{
\end_layout

\end_inset

Encouragement and Distortionary Effects of Conditional Cash Transfers
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Bryan Et Al (2021): Motivation
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Conditional Cash Transfers (CCTs) started in the late 90s in LatAm.
 By 2014 64 non-OECD countries had a CCT
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Payment is conditional on completing some behavior.
 Is this 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

better
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 than an Unconditional Cash Transfer (UCT)?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the behavior has a social benefit larger than its cost and would not
 be undertaken in the absence of the condition, CCT can be better than UCT
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
But CCT also requires monitoring compliance with the condition.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 a tradeoff.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Economic theory also suggests CCT can be distortionary if households undertake
 behavior with higher social cost than benefit in order to satisfy conditions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This paper presents theory and an experiment on migration to study these
 issues.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Bryan Et Al (2021): Theory
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Simple model to illustrate concepts.
 Framed as a migration decision but more widely applicable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Households in a community 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in N$
\end_inset

 are characterized by a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i},\hat{z}_{i}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\emph on
social
\emph default
 benefit of household 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 migrating, measured in $
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the household's 
\emph on
perceived
\emph default
 benefit of migrating
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Under-investment:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i}\geq0$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}_{i}<0$
\end_inset

: Household 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

should
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 migrate, but does not
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Over-investment: 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $z_{i}<0$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}_{i}\geq0$
\end_inset

: Household 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shouldn't
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 migrate, but it does
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Model can capture behavioral biases, (network) externalities etc.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Bryan Et Al (2021): Theory
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Assume away income effects and we can consider a CCT that pays households
 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 iff they migrate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
CCT has an 
\series bold
encouragement effect
\series default
 if there are households for whom 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}_{i}<0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i}\geq0$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}_{i}+m\geq0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
CCT has a 
\series bold
distortionary effect
\series default
 if there are households for whom 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}_{i}<0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i}<0$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}_{i}+m\geq0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Claim: 
\emph default
In a community of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 households, order them such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}_{1}<\hat{z}_{2}<\ldots<\hat{z}_{N}$
\end_inset

.
 If the household ordering also satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{1}<z_{2}<\ldots<z_{N}$
\end_inset

 then the social welfare gain from a CCT will be either i) monotonically
 increasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

; ii) monotonically decreasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

; or iii) inverted-U shape in 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Bryan Et Al (2021): Theory
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename pictures/BryanEtAl01.png
	height 100theight%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Bryan Et Al (2021): Experimental Design
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Labor demand/wages are low during pre-harvest season in many places
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Rural Eastern Indonesia, West Timor one such area.
 Some households send seasonal migrants to cities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Sampled 5 villages in Timor Tengga Utara (TTU) Regency in West Timor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
855 households interviewed, and 775 eligible: (i) 
\begin_inset Formula $\geq1$
\end_inset

 hh member aged 21+; (ii) land 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq200$
\end_inset

 Are (2 hectares).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Households randomized into either UCT of IDR 150K (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

$10) with no conditions; or CCT.
 CCT had to migrate, received half of transfer in origin village and half
 in the destination.
 Randomized into 3 groups: (1) Low (IDR 150K); (2) High (IDR 300K); (3)
 Low with surprise (unexpected extra 225K in destination)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Need (3) to try and disentangle selection effects they are interested in
 from direct effect of larger transfer.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
