\end_inset

Why Do People Stay Poor?
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Balboni et al.
 (2022): Motivation
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Questions in development economics don't get much bigger than 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Why do people stay poor?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Most poor individuals are employed but have low earnings.
 Why?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The poor have the same opportunities as everyone else, so it must be that
 they have traits that are unsuitable for other occupations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The poor do not have the same opportunities.
 They take low-earning jobs because they are born poor.
 A 
\series bold
Poverty Trap
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Distinguishing between these two hypotheses is 
\emph on
hard
\emph default
.
 Both have the same predictions for equilibrium allocation of people across
 occupations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To tell them apart need to observe what happens when you cross the threshold
 level of affluence to escape poverty trap.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Under view 1 you return to where you started
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Under view 2 you will escape poverty forever
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Balboni et al.
 (2022): Setting
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Test for poverty traps using BRAC's Targeting the Ultra-Poor (TUP) program
 in Bangladesh.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Bandiera et al.
 (2017) study impacts using data on 23K hhs in 1,309 villages in 13 poorest
 districts.
 Of these, 6K hhs are considered 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

extremely poor
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Program offers one-off transfer of productive assets (a cow in 91% of cases)
 and training to use it to women from ultra-poor hhs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Baseline survey in 2007, then follow-ups in 2009, 2011, 2014 and 2018 (11
 years!)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


